WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.660 --> 00:00:05.506
Prof: We're going to
continue with the lecture on the

00:00:05.506 --> 00:00:08.570
Gospel of John that I talked
about last time.

00:00:08.570 --> 00:00:12.038
I want to finish up with some
of the material on John that I

00:00:12.038 --> 00:00:14.390
didn't get to as much as I'd
like to,

00:00:14.390 --> 00:00:16.540
and then we're going to switch
to the letters of John--

00:00:16.540 --> 00:00:18.307
1,2, and 3 John,
so we're going to do both of

00:00:18.307 --> 00:00:18.910
those things.
 

00:00:18.910 --> 00:00:22.035
Now, remember,
the rubric under which today's

00:00:22.035 --> 00:00:26.439
lecture happens is not just the
Gospel of John and not just the

00:00:26.439 --> 00:00:27.860
letters of John.
 

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:31.169
As I've brought up several
times, the method that I'm

00:00:31.169 --> 00:00:35.114
teaching you right now in this
class is the historical critical

00:00:35.114 --> 00:00:38.932
method as it was developed in
the twentieth century in Europe

00:00:38.932 --> 00:00:40.460
and North America.
 

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:44.053
This means that we're not
reading these texts for just

00:00:44.053 --> 00:00:47.442
what the texts say about
theology or even the early

00:00:47.442 --> 00:00:50.305
church or doctrine,
or ethics or something like

00:00:50.305 --> 00:00:50.580
that.
 

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:53.390
We're trying to read the text
in a way against the very

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:54.640
intention of the text.
 

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:58.438
We're taking the text as being
something like a window that we

00:00:58.438 --> 00:01:00.929
can look through to try to
construct,

00:01:00.929 --> 00:01:03.869
as best as we can guess at it,
what kind of social context,

00:01:03.869 --> 00:01:06.530
what kind of political context,
what kind of church,

00:01:06.530 --> 00:01:11.037
what kind of social groups
produced these texts and found

00:01:11.037 --> 00:01:14.110
them to be compelling,
found them to be believable.

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:17.060
There are lots of other ways to
read this.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:19.167
Obviously the Gospel of John is
very important for Christian

00:01:19.167 --> 00:01:19.560
doctrine.
 

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:22.420
It's the most Christological of
the Gospels,

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:24.310
it has the highest form of
Christology,

00:01:24.310 --> 00:01:27.849
that is the Christology--it's
the most divine rather than

00:01:27.849 --> 00:01:31.769
simply being human and so it's
very important for doctrine,

00:01:31.769 --> 00:01:33.030
and for theology, and for faith.
 

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:36.152
What I'm doing right now is
just one particular way of

00:01:36.152 --> 00:01:39.141
reading,
which is reading this text as a

00:01:39.141 --> 00:01:41.598
clue,
as a series of clues and traces

00:01:41.598 --> 00:01:45.393
that we might use to reconstruct
what we think was going on in

00:01:45.393 --> 00:01:48.690
the first century with the
growth of Christianity.

00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:51.470
I'm trying to show you by this
that there are different kinds

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:53.879
of Christianity that grew up in
different places,

00:01:53.879 --> 00:01:56.230
different geographical
settings, and different times.

00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:59.289
So what we call Johannine
Christianity is what we're going

00:01:59.289 --> 00:02:00.468
to talk about today.
 

00:02:00.468 --> 00:02:02.817
And we're also--one of the
wonderful things about the John

00:02:02.817 --> 00:02:04.590
literature is that by having the
Gospel,

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:08.205
which is written at one time,
and then having 1 John which is

00:02:08.205 --> 00:02:11.218
the letter written after that
time we can tell,

00:02:11.218 --> 00:02:15.276
that shows us a development of
this form of Christianity and

00:02:15.276 --> 00:02:18.932
than by having 2 and 3 John,
which we believe were written

00:02:18.932 --> 00:02:22.300
still later than 1 John,
that gives us a third stage.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:25.718
In fact, what I'm going to be
talking about is three or four

00:02:25.718 --> 00:02:29.022
stages in the development of
Johannine Christianity as one

00:02:29.022 --> 00:02:31.400
branch of early Christian
literature.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:34.655
In order to do this--I talked
last time about how one of the

00:02:34.655 --> 00:02:38.131
things going on in the Gospel of
John is Jesus and the Gospel of

00:02:38.131 --> 00:02:41.497
John seems to start off lots of
conversations and they lead to

00:02:41.497 --> 00:02:44.172
division,
so the causation of division is

00:02:44.172 --> 00:02:47.699
one of the themes of the Gospel
of John and to show that we're

00:02:47.699 --> 00:02:50.360
going to walk through a couple
of chapters.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.440
First look at chapter 3,
this is the story of Nicodemus,

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.210
so get your Bibles out and
follow along with me,

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:59.300
because we're going to look at
this in depth and then we're

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:00.598
going to look at chapter 8 a
bit,

00:03:00.598 --> 00:03:02.020
and then we're going to move
off.

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.431
I said division is the issue,
so what we're going to talk

00:03:04.431 --> 00:03:05.810
about is what the division is.
 

00:03:05.810 --> 00:03:10.199
One of the ways that this
author does this is he sets up

00:03:10.199 --> 00:03:15.150
Jesus in these dialogues that
don't actually work very well.

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:18.909
Jesus is not good on
interpersonal communication in

00:03:18.909 --> 00:03:20.490
the Gospel of John.
 

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:23.060
I'm sorry to have to tell you
that.

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:24.810
We'll talk about why that's the
case.

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:27.935
Jesus talks in riddles,
so the question we're going to

00:03:27.935 --> 00:03:31.650
have is why does Jesus talk in
riddles in the Gospel of John?

00:03:31.650 --> 00:03:34.878
What do we get out of that?
 

00:03:34.878 --> 00:03:39.720
Chapter 3, "There was a
Pharisee named Nicodemus,

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:42.184
a leader of the Jews,
he came to Jesus by night and

00:03:42.184 --> 00:03:44.021
said to him"--
now by night,

00:03:44.021 --> 00:03:47.604
darkness is kind of a thematic
issue in the Gospel of John,

00:03:47.604 --> 00:03:48.160
right?
 

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.348
Notice I'm not going to bring
up all these themes this time,

00:03:50.348 --> 00:03:53.335
but keep noticing these themes
that I talked about last time as

00:03:53.335 --> 00:03:55.310
they occur even in this little
passage.

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:57.535
"Rabbi,
we know that you are a teacher

00:03:57.535 --> 00:04:00.568
who has come from God,
and no one else can do these

00:04:00.568 --> 00:04:03.990
signs that you do apart from the
presence of God."

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:06.658
Jesus answered him,
"Very truly I tell you,

00:04:06.658 --> 00:04:09.841
no one can see the kingdom of
God without being born from

00:04:09.841 --> 00:04:10.750
above."
 

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:16.329
How the hell does that follow
from what Nicodemus just said?

00:04:16.329 --> 00:04:19.122
He's gives Jesus a compliment,
"you're a teacher from

00:04:19.122 --> 00:04:21.180
God, no one else can do these
signs, ...

00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:22.788
apart from the presence of
Godâ€¦,"

00:04:22.788 --> 00:04:23.992
Jesus says,
"No one can see the

00:04:23.992 --> 00:04:25.266
kingdom of"--
what is there,

00:04:25.266 --> 00:04:26.410
is there a thank you?
 

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:31.009
Can Jesus say,
"You're smart"?

00:04:31.009 --> 00:04:32.930
"You just got something
there"?

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:36.100
No, Jesus starts off changing
the subject.

00:04:36.100 --> 00:04:39.240
Jesus changes the subject in
the Gospel of John quite a lot.

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:43.002
"No one can see the
Kingdom of God without being

00:04:43.002 --> 00:04:44.740
born from above."
 

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:47.589
Now you're reading it in
English translation.

00:04:47.589 --> 00:04:50.057
My text just said "from
above," does anybody's

00:04:50.057 --> 00:04:52.257
translation have something
different there besides

00:04:52.257 --> 00:04:53.470
"from above"?
 

00:04:53.470 --> 00:04:53.970
Student: 
&gt;

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:57.612
Prof: "Without
being born anew,"

00:04:57.612 --> 00:04:59.129
"again."
 

00:04:59.129 --> 00:05:01.845
The problem is the Greek
actually can be translated

00:05:01.845 --> 00:05:04.778
either "being born
again" or "being born

00:05:04.778 --> 00:05:07.221
all over again,"
or "being born from

00:05:07.221 --> 00:05:08.199
above."
 

00:05:08.199 --> 00:05:10.149
The same Greek word means both
things.

00:05:10.149 --> 00:05:12.500
Now this is the one place,
basically,

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:16.338
in the Bible which born-again
kind of language comes out,

00:05:16.338 --> 00:05:18.774
so it's kind of ironic that
there's whole branches of

00:05:18.774 --> 00:05:21.442
American Christianity which base
their entire theology and

00:05:21.442 --> 00:05:24.278
ideology on the idea,
have you been born again?

00:05:24.278 --> 00:05:26.117
Because really it's just from
this passage,

00:05:26.117 --> 00:05:28.480
the other Gospels don't talk
about being born again.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.800
It's a rather rare metaphor in
early Christianity.

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:33.629
It comes from this chapter
right here,

00:05:33.629 --> 00:05:36.892
and it comes from a Greek word
that could be just as easily

00:05:36.892 --> 00:05:40.098
translated "be born from
above" as "be born

00:05:40.098 --> 00:05:41.000
again."
 

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:42.687
My English
translation--translators have

00:05:42.687 --> 00:05:45.206
decided to translated,
"from above,"

00:05:45.206 --> 00:05:48.767
but notice it's confusing for
the hearer because Nicodemus

00:05:48.767 --> 00:05:51.329
then answers as if he heard it
to be,

00:05:51.329 --> 00:05:55.410
"being born again,"
so Nicodemus said to him,

00:05:55.410 --> 00:05:58.660
"How can anyone be born
after having grown old?

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:02.238
Can one enter a second time
into the mother's womb and be

00:06:02.238 --> 00:06:03.069
born?"
 

00:06:03.069 --> 00:06:07.567
Jesus said, "Nicodemus I'm
speaking metaphorically and

00:06:07.567 --> 00:06:11.105
spiritually here,
you need to understand that I

00:06:11.105 --> 00:06:15.146
don't mean particularly that
someone has to be actually born

00:06:15.146 --> 00:06:18.160
physically from their mother
again."

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:20.720
No, Jesus doesn't say any of
that, right?

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.100
That's what Jesus should have
said,

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:26.605
probably, if Jesus really
wanted to communicate with

00:06:26.605 --> 00:06:28.600
Nicodemus,
but apparently,

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:32.853
in John, Jesus is not that
interested in communicating very

00:06:32.853 --> 00:06:36.300
directly with Nicodemus because
Jesus says,

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:39.684
"Truly I tell you,
no one can enter the Kingdom of

00:06:39.684 --> 00:06:42.879
God without being born of water
and spirit."

00:06:42.879 --> 00:06:45.910
What the hell does that mean?
 

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:49.416
"What is born of the flesh
is flesh, and what is born of

00:06:49.416 --> 00:06:50.759
the spirit is spirit.
 

00:06:50.759 --> 00:06:53.786
Do not be astonished that I
said to you, 'You must be born

00:06:53.786 --> 00:06:54.529
from above.'
 

00:06:54.529 --> 00:06:58.189
The wind blows where it
chooses, and you hear the sound

00:06:58.189 --> 00:07:01.983
of it but you do not know where
it comes from or where it

00:07:01.983 --> 00:07:03.000
goes."
 

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.990
What does that mean?
 

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:08.458
Does it help you to know the
Greek word translated here

00:07:08.458 --> 00:07:11.411
"spirit"
is also the Greek word which

00:07:11.411 --> 00:07:14.110
can be translated as
"wind."

00:07:14.110 --> 00:07:17.855
Notice that the Gospel of John
is playing with you with puns,

00:07:17.855 --> 00:07:20.540
there's already two puns in
this passage.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:23.870
One, does the Greek word--is
the Greek word "being born

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:26.750
again" or is it "born
from above"?

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:29.766
Well you're not told in the
text, in fact it sounds like it

00:07:29.766 --> 00:07:31.430
may mean a little bit of both.
 

00:07:31.430 --> 00:07:33.478
Is this Greek word,
pneuma,

00:07:33.478 --> 00:07:37.329
is it supposed to represent the
spirit as a theological term or

00:07:37.329 --> 00:07:40.250
is it supposed to represent
breath or wind?

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:43.550
It seems to be doing double
duty.

00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:46.074
Anyway, with all that stuff
about wind blowing where it

00:07:46.074 --> 00:07:48.357
will,
so it is with everyone who is

00:07:48.357 --> 00:07:52.500
born of the spirit Nicodemus
tries one more time said to him,

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:54.100
"How can these things
be?"

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:56.286
In other words,
Jesus can you give me an

00:07:56.286 --> 00:07:58.699
explanation of what you're
talking about?

00:07:58.699 --> 00:08:00.310
It's not an unreasonable
request.

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:02.690
Jesus answered,
"Are you a teacher of

00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:05.480
Israel and you do not understand
these things?

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:10.060
[Well that's helpful.]
Truly I tell you.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:12.552
we speak of what we know and
testify to what we've seen,

00:08:12.552 --> 00:08:14.319
yet you do not receive our
testimony.

00:08:14.319 --> 00:08:16.490
If I had told you about earthly
things and you do not believe,

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:18.589
how will you believe if I tell
you about heavenly things?

00:08:18.589 --> 00:08:20.716
No one has ascended into heaven
except the one who descended

00:08:20.716 --> 00:08:21.800
from heaven, the Son of Man.
 

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:23.769
And just as Moses lifted up the
servant in the wilderness,

00:08:23.769 --> 00:08:25.560
so the Son of Man must be
lifted up,

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:29.230
that whoever believes in him
may have eternal life."

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:31.939
Well at this point Nicodemus
just gives up.

00:08:31.939 --> 00:08:33.995
We don't hear about Nicodemus
anymore in the story so

00:08:33.995 --> 00:08:36.089
apparently he's decided,
I can't get a straight answer

00:08:36.089 --> 00:08:36.879
out of this guy.
 

00:08:36.879 --> 00:08:40.533
Notice also how Jesus starts
off in a dialogical stance with

00:08:40.533 --> 00:08:43.320
Nicodemus but never answers his
questions,

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:45.110
and then Jesus almost gets kind
of,

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:47.740
well nasty, toward the end.
 

00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:50.754
He kind of just almost insults
Nicodemus rather than just

00:08:50.754 --> 00:08:52.210
explaining what he means.
 

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:55.916
This is kind of the way Jesus
sometimes talks in the Gospel of

00:08:55.916 --> 00:08:58.590
John, and my question is going
to be, why?

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:01.730
Is Jesus just lacking in social
skills?

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:21.585
Look in 8:31,
another little interesting

00:09:21.585 --> 00:09:23.240
dialogue.
 

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:26.791
Jesus has been teaching and now
"Jesus said to the Jews who

00:09:26.791 --> 00:09:28.370
had believed in him."
 

00:09:28.370 --> 00:09:32.039
Now notice the scene starts
out--often in the Gospel of John

00:09:32.039 --> 00:09:35.711
the Jews are talked about as if
they're something other than

00:09:35.711 --> 00:09:36.519
Jesus is.
 

00:09:36.519 --> 00:09:38.298
Of course Jesus is a Jew,
his disciples are Jews,

00:09:38.298 --> 00:09:41.139
they're all Jews in this story
but the term "the

00:09:41.139 --> 00:09:44.033
Jews" gets packed in the
Gospel of John with this

00:09:44.033 --> 00:09:47.035
otherness and this is a
reflection of the sectarianism I

00:09:47.035 --> 00:09:48.620
talked about last time.
 

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:51.304
Now notice Jesus is now
starting to talk to the Jews

00:09:51.304 --> 00:09:52.779
who believe in him.
 

00:09:52.779 --> 00:09:54.462
These are not the Jews who have
rejected him,

00:09:54.462 --> 00:09:56.759
that's very important to see at
this point in the chapter.

00:09:56.759 --> 00:09:58.490
These are the Jews who now
believe in him.

00:09:58.490 --> 00:10:01.394
"If you continue in my
word you are truly my disciples

00:10:01.394 --> 00:10:04.097
and you will know the truth and
the truth will make you

00:10:04.097 --> 00:10:04.850
free."
 

00:10:04.850 --> 00:10:07.875
They answered him,
"We are the descendants of

00:10:07.875 --> 00:10:10.778
Abraham and have never been
slaves to anyone.

00:10:10.778 --> 00:10:14.210
What do you mean by saying you
will be made free?"

00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:16.960
Jesus answered them,
"Well I was speaking

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:18.000
metaphorically.
 

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.136
I meant that,
let's say you're slaves to sin

00:10:21.136 --> 00:10:25.004
and, if you follow me,
then I will make you truly free

00:10:25.004 --> 00:10:27.850
in a spiritual sense,
I mean."

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:30.289
That's not what Jesus does,
right?

00:10:30.289 --> 00:10:32.818
All right 34:
Jesus answered them,

00:10:32.818 --> 00:10:35.498
"Very truly I tell you,
everyone who commits sin is a

00:10:35.498 --> 00:10:36.250
slave to sin.
 

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:38.528
The slave does not have a
permanent place in the

00:10:38.528 --> 00:10:39.110
household.
 

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:42.035
The son has a place there
forever, so if the son makes you

00:10:42.035 --> 00:10:43.678
free, you will be free indeed.
 

00:10:43.678 --> 00:10:45.710
I know that you are descendants
of Abraham,

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:50.048
yet you look for an opportunity
to kill me [Wait a minute,

00:10:50.048 --> 00:10:54.365
Jesus, these are the people who
believe in you.]

00:10:54.365 --> 00:10:58.590
because there's no place in you
for my word.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:00.110
I declare what I have seen in
the Father's presence.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:01.932
As for you, you should do what
you have heard from the

00:11:01.932 --> 00:11:02.450
Father."
 

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:04.889
They answered him,
Well Abraham's our father,

00:11:04.889 --> 00:11:05.610
we're Jews.
 

00:11:05.610 --> 00:11:07.551
Jesus said to them,
"If you are Abraham's

00:11:07.551 --> 00:11:09.580
children you would be doing what
Abraham did.

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:11.905
But now you are trying to kill
me and a man who has told you

00:11:11.905 --> 00:11:14.389
the truth that I heard from God,
that's not what Abraham did.

00:11:14.389 --> 00:11:16.428
You are indeed doing what your
father said."

00:11:16.428 --> 00:11:18.653
They said to him,
"We are not bastards,

00:11:18.653 --> 00:11:21.499
we are not illegitimate
children, we have one father God

00:11:21.499 --> 00:11:22.120
Himself.
 

00:11:22.120 --> 00:11:24.169
So they try another tactic,
well if he won't be satisfied

00:11:24.169 --> 00:11:25.561
with Abraham as being the
Father, okay,

00:11:25.561 --> 00:11:26.769
we'll have God as our Father.
 

00:11:26.769 --> 00:11:28.725
Jesus said to them,
"If God were your Father

00:11:28.725 --> 00:11:30.273
you would love me,
for I came from God,

00:11:30.273 --> 00:11:31.168
and now I am here.
 

00:11:31.168 --> 00:11:32.840
I did not come of my own,
but he sent me.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:34.250
Why do you not understand what
I say?

00:11:34.250 --> 00:11:35.389
Is it because you cannot accept
my word?

00:11:35.389 --> 00:11:36.690
You are from your father the
devil."

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:40.480
The devil?
 

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:42.519
These are the people who
believe in him,

00:11:42.519 --> 00:11:45.820
and Jesus ends up the whole
thing as I told--

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:49.351
they finally end up saying,
yeah the Jews in verse 48 the

00:11:49.351 --> 00:11:51.432
Jews are saying,
"Are we not right in

00:11:51.432 --> 00:11:53.408
saying that you are a Samaritan
and have a demon?"

00:11:53.408 --> 00:11:56.865
Now they're both being
antagonistic,

00:11:56.865 --> 00:12:02.789
and finally the chapter ends
way down there as I talked about

00:12:02.789 --> 00:12:06.265
last time verse 56,
"Your ancestor Abraham

00:12:06.265 --> 00:12:08.355
rejoiced that he would see my
day, he saw it and was

00:12:08.355 --> 00:12:08.928
glad."
 

00:12:08.928 --> 00:12:10.595
Then the Jews said to him,
"You are not yet fifty

00:12:10.595 --> 00:12:12.009
years old, and have you seen
Abraham?"

00:12:12.009 --> 00:12:15.230
Jesus said to him,
"Very truly I tell you,

00:12:15.230 --> 00:12:17.538
before Abraham was,
I am."

00:12:17.538 --> 00:12:20.572
There's that strong
Christological claim of Jesus

00:12:20.572 --> 00:12:23.532
being God himself,
and of course they picked up

00:12:23.532 --> 00:12:26.190
stones to throw at him,
but Jesus hid himself and went

00:12:26.190 --> 00:12:26.950
out of the temple.
 

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:30.327
Notice there are these things
going on, Jesus speaks in

00:12:30.327 --> 00:12:32.330
riddles in the Gospel of John.
 

00:12:32.330 --> 00:12:37.148
Jesus does not do what a good
Yale instructor is supposed to

00:12:37.148 --> 00:12:40.169
do, which is explain things to
you.

00:12:40.169 --> 00:12:42.070
Jesus talks in riddles.
 

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:45.379
When they ask questions he
responds in--with non-sequiturs.

00:12:45.379 --> 00:12:49.238
And then when they act like
they want to believe in him he

00:12:49.238 --> 00:12:52.418
pushes them and then starts
picking at them,

00:12:52.418 --> 00:12:55.431
and accusing them of stuff and
eventually the scene ends up

00:12:55.431 --> 00:12:57.298
with everybody is all
frustrated,

00:12:57.298 --> 00:12:59.308
Jesus is accusing them of
trying to kill him,

00:12:59.308 --> 00:13:02.889
and sure enough then they do
start to try to kill him.

00:13:02.889 --> 00:13:07.014
Notice how in the Gospel of
John repeatedly these issues

00:13:07.014 --> 00:13:09.039
come down to Christology.
 

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:11.418
Who is the person of Jesus?
 

00:13:11.418 --> 00:13:15.144
The point at which they pick up
the stones to throw at him is

00:13:15.144 --> 00:13:18.000
when he makes this claim by
quoting Exodus,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.460
the very name of God,
that Jesus himself is God.

00:13:23.460 --> 00:13:26.740
Now with all that going on
let's look at how this then

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:29.649
plays itself out in the first
letter of John.

00:13:34.038 --> 00:13:37.870
Just to back up,
remember how diverse we're

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:41.325
finding Christianity,
and we're going to start seeing

00:13:41.325 --> 00:13:43.570
that diversity now representing
itself in Christology.

00:13:43.570 --> 00:13:47.529
We have seen it already in
geography, right?

00:13:47.529 --> 00:13:49.687
We've seen that,
and according to the Book of

00:13:49.687 --> 00:13:51.755
Acts,
the Gospel spread out in

00:13:51.755 --> 00:13:54.899
concentric circles from
Jerusalem to Judea,

00:13:54.899 --> 00:13:56.519
to Samaria to the ends of the
earth,

00:13:56.519 --> 00:13:59.514
but we also saw how in Acts if
you read it critically between

00:13:59.514 --> 00:14:02.360
the lines you can see it didn't
really spread that way.

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:05.485
There were anonymous Christians
who went off out of Jerusalem

00:14:05.485 --> 00:14:08.298
after a certain period of
persecution and they took the

00:14:08.298 --> 00:14:11.110
message to Cyrene and to
different parts of the east of

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:14.080
the Mediterranean and these were
anonymous people,

00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:15.340
we don't know them,
they weren't Peter.

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:17.879
Then later Paul and Barnabas
take things around,

00:14:17.879 --> 00:14:20.437
and Phillip goes off to
Samaria, and maybe there's this

00:14:20.437 --> 00:14:23.090
Ethiopian eunuch in the Book of
Acts who's converted,

00:14:23.090 --> 00:14:25.210
and he may take the Gospel back
to Ethiopia.

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:28.211
So the spread of Christianity
historically was much messier

00:14:28.211 --> 00:14:31.317
then it really is portrayed in
any straightforward way in the

00:14:31.317 --> 00:14:32.250
New Testament.
 

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:35.085
It seemed to have been spread
by just people going to their

00:14:35.085 --> 00:14:38.018
home villages and hometowns and
taking back this message that

00:14:38.018 --> 00:14:39.730
they heard in different places.
 

00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:42.855
The way the Gospel spreads,
the way Christianity spreads is

00:14:42.855 --> 00:14:43.610
differently.
 

00:14:43.610 --> 00:14:46.139
We saw, for example,
that in Thomasine Christianity,

00:14:46.139 --> 00:14:48.828
which seems to have been very
popular in Syria and then all

00:14:48.828 --> 00:14:51.523
the way into India,
that's a form of Christianity

00:14:51.523 --> 00:14:55.044
that's slightly different from
the form of Christianity that's

00:14:55.044 --> 00:14:56.950
rising up in Rome at the time.
 

00:14:56.950 --> 00:15:00.260
Although church tradition says
that Peter was the one who took

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:03.028
the Gospel to Rome and founded
the church there,

00:15:03.028 --> 00:15:06.056
well, we have good reasons as
you can tell why we historians

00:15:06.056 --> 00:15:07.029
tend to doubt that.
 

00:15:07.029 --> 00:15:07.389
Why?
 

00:15:07.389 --> 00:15:10.738
Because we attend--we believe
basically that again anonymous

00:15:10.738 --> 00:15:13.972
Christians who are lost to
history probably were the first

00:15:13.972 --> 00:15:16.129
ones who took the Gospel to
Rome,

00:15:16.129 --> 00:15:19.870
and then Peter became connected
--with that tradition.

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:22.418
There's a certain kind of
Christianity that's growing up

00:15:22.418 --> 00:15:24.207
in Rome,
there's another kind of

00:15:24.207 --> 00:15:27.100
Christianity that's growing up
in Syria and India,

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:29.937
there's another kind of
Christianity that's growing up

00:15:29.937 --> 00:15:32.509
in Antioch and in that part of
western Syria,

00:15:32.509 --> 00:15:34.538
and there's another kind of
Christianity we don't know

00:15:34.538 --> 00:15:36.719
anything about at this point
that's probably growing up in

00:15:36.719 --> 00:15:38.322
Egypt,
we just don't have enough

00:15:38.322 --> 00:15:40.879
sources to know what kind of
Christianity may have been

00:15:40.879 --> 00:15:41.970
growing up in Egypt.
 

00:15:41.970 --> 00:15:45.654
There's different geographical
regions experiencing different

00:15:45.654 --> 00:15:48.509
kinds of Christianity,
and those different kinds of

00:15:48.509 --> 00:15:51.009
Christianity are diverse with
respect to the Torah,

00:15:51.009 --> 00:15:52.440
the Jewish law right?
 

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:56.081
If there's another--if there is
still a form of Christianity

00:15:56.081 --> 00:15:59.663
that's predominantly Jewish
that's located in Jerusalem and

00:15:59.663 --> 00:16:02.379
it's led by James the brother of
Jesus,

00:16:02.379 --> 00:16:05.905
who seems to have been famous
for advocating a certain kind of

00:16:05.905 --> 00:16:09.490
law observant Torah obedient
form of discipleship to Jesus,

00:16:09.490 --> 00:16:12.048
then you've got a form of
Jewish Christianity that still

00:16:12.048 --> 00:16:14.989
seems to be keeping the law,
and we've seen that reflected

00:16:14.989 --> 00:16:16.850
possibly in the Gospel of
Matthew,

00:16:16.850 --> 00:16:20.307
with its teaching that the law
is still something that people

00:16:20.307 --> 00:16:21.230
ought to obey.
 

00:16:21.230 --> 00:16:23.966
We've seen though that the
Gospel of Mark teaches a

00:16:23.966 --> 00:16:26.597
Christianity that maybe it--
some people say Mark was

00:16:26.597 --> 00:16:28.894
written in Rome,
other people say maybe Mark was

00:16:28.894 --> 00:16:31.514
written in Syria or in Galilee,
but it's some kind of

00:16:31.514 --> 00:16:33.720
Christianity that's now
predominantly Gentile,

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:35.529
although it still has Jewish
elements,

00:16:35.529 --> 00:16:38.070
but these are people who are
not keeping the law.

00:16:38.070 --> 00:16:40.183
They seem to believe that they
don't have to keep the Jewish

00:16:40.183 --> 00:16:40.399
law.
 

00:16:40.399 --> 00:16:43.601
Then we've got the form of
Christianity in Luke that we saw

00:16:43.601 --> 00:16:47.424
where the Torah,
the law, represents a certain

00:16:47.424 --> 00:16:52.095
an ethnic tradition of the Jews,
so if you're Jewish you should

00:16:52.095 --> 00:16:54.831
keep the law but if you're a
Gentile you don't need to keep

00:16:54.831 --> 00:16:55.350
the law.
 

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:58.941
Then we saw from the Gospel of
Thomas and the Gospel of John

00:16:58.941 --> 00:17:01.620
where is the concern about the
law at all?

00:17:01.620 --> 00:17:02.808
It's not really there.
 

00:17:02.808 --> 00:17:05.130
You can read all the way
through the Gospel of John,

00:17:05.130 --> 00:17:07.318
sure there are some
controversies about the Sabbath,

00:17:07.318 --> 00:17:08.640
about what you can do on the
Sabbath,

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:13.246
but disputes about observation
of Jewish law are not really at

00:17:13.246 --> 00:17:17.776
issue in the Gospel of Thomas
and they're not really at issue

00:17:17.776 --> 00:17:19.740
in the Gospel of John.
 

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:24.430
What is at issue in the Gospel
of John is Christology.

00:17:24.430 --> 00:17:25.598
What do you believe about Jesus?
 

00:17:25.598 --> 00:17:28.420
Let's look at the different
kinds of Christologies you get

00:17:28.420 --> 00:17:31.390
in early Christianity too before
we move onto the letters.

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:36.890
First Mark, the Gospel of Mark,
what is Mark's Christology?

00:17:36.890 --> 00:17:38.529
What is his doctrine of Christ?
 

00:17:38.529 --> 00:17:41.262
Well for one thing,
according to Mark,

00:17:41.262 --> 00:17:45.104
Jesus is the Son of God,
now that doesn't necessarily

00:17:45.104 --> 00:17:48.871
mean yet that Jesus is
completely divine or equal to

00:17:48.871 --> 00:17:49.608
God.
 

00:17:49.608 --> 00:17:53.144
You can be called a Son of God
without necessarily being God

00:17:53.144 --> 00:17:55.660
himself in this period of
Christianity,

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:58.608
but at least Mark certainly
considers Jesus the Son of God.

00:17:58.608 --> 00:18:01.923
He also, though,
considers Jesus to be the

00:18:01.923 --> 00:18:05.803
Messiah, the Christ,
who has to suffer and Jesus'

00:18:05.803 --> 00:18:10.410
suffering is for the purpose of
ransoming us sinners.

00:18:10.410 --> 00:18:14.295
Now the Christology that Mark's
working with is Jesus is the

00:18:14.295 --> 00:18:15.961
Messiah,
the Son of God,

00:18:15.961 --> 00:18:19.345
it's mandated that he suffers,
so it's God's will that the

00:18:19.345 --> 00:18:20.160
Messiah suffer.
 

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:22.611
And that's one of the reasons
he writes his Gospel is to

00:18:22.611 --> 00:18:25.374
convince his readers that Jesus'
suffering and execution wasn't

00:18:25.374 --> 00:18:27.380
an accident and it wasn't a
catastrophe,

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:29.410
and it wasn't a calamity,
it was God's will,

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:31.130
it needed to happen.
 

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:35.490
So the suffering Son of God is
part of Mark's Christology.

00:18:35.490 --> 00:18:38.817
If you get to Luke,
as I've said before,

00:18:38.817 --> 00:18:43.510
this whole idea that Jesus'
death was a ransom is not in

00:18:43.510 --> 00:18:44.279
Luke.
 

00:18:44.279 --> 00:18:47.662
In fact, Luke excises that part
of Mark when he's copying that

00:18:47.662 --> 00:18:50.413
part of Mark,
and he leaves out that ransom

00:18:50.413 --> 00:18:54.269
passage from Mark because that
doesn't fit his Christology.

00:18:54.269 --> 00:18:57.189
For the Christology of Luke,
do you remember,

00:18:57.189 --> 00:18:59.842
Luke and Acts,
what is the Christology of

00:18:59.842 --> 00:19:00.440
Luke?
 

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:03.730
Anybody want to venture a
remembrance?

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:06.338
The martyr prophet exactly.
 

00:19:06.338 --> 00:19:11.098
Jesus is the martyr prophet
who's an example for Stephen,

00:19:11.098 --> 00:19:14.900
or Paul, or all of us who are
followers of Jesus,

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:16.923
we're all martyr prophets,
we're called to be martyr

00:19:16.923 --> 00:19:19.328
prophets,
that's not a ransom for many.

00:19:19.328 --> 00:19:23.608
Luke doesn't have a doctrine of
the atonement,

00:19:23.608 --> 00:19:28.030
the Christian doctrine that
says, the death of Jesus was to

00:19:28.030 --> 00:19:32.757
pay for the sins of humanity or
to redeem human beings from the

00:19:32.757 --> 00:19:36.288
debts of sin,
so that's Luke's.

00:19:36.288 --> 00:19:39.924
The Gospel of Thomas,
there's no death at all in the

00:19:39.924 --> 00:19:41.279
Gospel of Thomas.
 

00:19:41.279 --> 00:19:44.838
The Christology of the Gospel
of Thomas though is that Jesus

00:19:44.838 --> 00:19:48.460
comes across as practically an
already resurrected figure.

00:19:48.460 --> 00:19:51.258
He's a knower,
he's a figure of wisdom who's

00:19:51.258 --> 00:19:54.056
come from the Father,
who's come from above,

00:19:54.056 --> 00:19:57.568
and he comes to give his
disciples true knowledge.

00:19:57.568 --> 00:20:02.980
So Jesus as the revealer of
hidden knowledge is the main

00:20:02.980 --> 00:20:06.720
Christology of the Gospel of
Thomas.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:11.170
Now the Gospel of John,
this is when you get closest to

00:20:11.170 --> 00:20:14.880
what will be seen as orthodox
Christianity.

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:20.172
A lot of orthodox Christology
was set at least,

00:20:20.172 --> 00:20:26.500
at one of the main periods,
at the Council of Nicaea.

00:20:26.500 --> 00:20:35.838
So we call this the Council of
Nicaea in 325 of our era CE,

00:20:35.838 --> 00:20:38.220
there was a council called
together by the Emperor

00:20:38.220 --> 00:20:41.328
Constantine who was tired of all
these Christians squabbling,

00:20:41.328 --> 00:20:45.258
especially about Christology,
and he got bishops and people

00:20:45.258 --> 00:20:48.188
from around the empire,
and he tried to get them to

00:20:48.188 --> 00:20:49.140
come to an agreement.
 

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:53.259
They wrote what has come down
to be called the Nicene Creed.

00:20:53.259 --> 00:20:57.480
And a lot of Christians,
Roman Catholics,

00:20:57.480 --> 00:21:00.588
Episcopalians,
Anglicans, some other churches,

00:21:00.588 --> 00:21:04.779
will actually say the Nicene
Creed in church as part of the

00:21:04.779 --> 00:21:05.720
literature.
 

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:08.000
Can anybody say it?
 

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.410
We believe in--some of you know
it,

00:21:12.410 --> 00:21:15.836
yes, you know the Nicene Creed,
so that Nicene Creed about

00:21:15.836 --> 00:21:17.893
Jesus being very God,
from very God,

00:21:17.893 --> 00:21:19.338
God from God,
light from light,

00:21:19.338 --> 00:21:22.182
begotten not made,
because that was one of the

00:21:22.182 --> 00:21:25.626
Christological--
so was Jesus Son of God because

00:21:25.626 --> 00:21:29.796
he was born from eternity as
divine or did God say at one

00:21:29.796 --> 00:21:34.336
point okay he's a really good
guy I'm going to graduate him to

00:21:34.336 --> 00:21:35.900
divinity status?
 

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:38.470
That was one Christology.
 

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:41.913
The Nicene Creed said,
no, Jesus did not become divine

00:21:41.913 --> 00:21:43.410
he always was divine.
 

00:21:43.410 --> 00:21:47.500
The orthodox Christology was
set to a great extent by the

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:51.928
Nicene Creed in 325,
but how do we get from the year

00:21:51.928 --> 00:21:56.115
30 when Jesus is crucified,
the year 70 when the Jerusalem

00:21:56.115 --> 00:21:59.076
temple is destroyed and the
Gospel of Mark may have been

00:21:59.076 --> 00:22:01.698
published,
the 50s when Paul was writing

00:22:01.698 --> 00:22:03.939
his letters,
maybe a year in the 90s when

00:22:03.939 --> 00:22:07.361
the Gospel of John is writing,
from those times all the way to

00:22:07.361 --> 00:22:11.144
year 325 where there's a whole
lot of fighting going on between

00:22:11.144 --> 00:22:14.683
Christians trying to solidify
what the orthodox Christology

00:22:14.683 --> 00:22:15.598
should be?
 

00:22:15.598 --> 00:22:17.618
Of these different sources
we've talked about,

00:22:17.618 --> 00:22:20.875
the one that comes the closest
to the Nicene Creed is this

00:22:20.875 --> 00:22:22.990
Christology of the Gospel of
John,

00:22:22.990 --> 00:22:26.450
because according to John,
Jesus is fully God,

00:22:26.450 --> 00:22:31.618
co-equal with the Father,
he's I am,

00:22:31.618 --> 00:22:34.192
that is identifying himself
with the figure who appeared to

00:22:34.192 --> 00:22:37.288
Moses in the burning bush,
he's the descending and

00:22:37.288 --> 00:22:41.114
ascending redeemer,
he's also the lamb of God

00:22:41.114 --> 00:22:45.914
sacrificed for the people,
and in his sacrifice he takes

00:22:45.914 --> 00:22:48.200
away the sins of the world.
 

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:52.089
All those elements that would
end up becoming orthodox

00:22:52.089 --> 00:22:54.586
Christianity,
orthodox Christology,

00:22:54.586 --> 00:22:57.890
those can be found in the
Gospel of John.

00:22:57.890 --> 00:23:00.519
Now how do we get from there to
1 John?

00:23:00.519 --> 00:23:02.078
Any questions about that?
 

00:23:02.078 --> 00:23:04.517
What I want you to really see
is I want you to be able to

00:23:04.517 --> 00:23:06.430
anchor down,
not just take my word for it

00:23:06.430 --> 00:23:08.618
that well,
Professor Martin knows all

00:23:08.618 --> 00:23:11.488
things about all things,
and he tells me that there are

00:23:11.488 --> 00:23:13.682
these different Christology's
and these different early

00:23:13.682 --> 00:23:15.955
Christian documents and so
that's what I'm going to write

00:23:15.955 --> 00:23:16.809
back on a paper.
 

00:23:16.809 --> 00:23:17.390
I don't want that.
 

00:23:17.390 --> 00:23:20.113
What I want you to do is be
able to actually anchor down

00:23:20.113 --> 00:23:22.736
these ideas into these
particular texts that come from

00:23:22.736 --> 00:23:25.460
particular different places in
early Christianity,

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:29.859
so any questions about that?
 

00:23:29.859 --> 00:23:30.618
Yes sir?
 

00:23:30.618 --> 00:23:33.509
Student: 
&gt;

00:23:33.509 --> 00:23:35.704
Prof: The Christology of
Matthew is quite a bit like

00:23:35.704 --> 00:23:35.970
Mark.
 

00:23:35.970 --> 00:23:39.093
Matthew also believes that the
death of Jesus,

00:23:39.093 --> 00:23:42.007
for example,
was as a ransom for people and

00:23:42.007 --> 00:23:42.910
for sins.
 

00:23:42.910 --> 00:23:46.827
Matthew also believes that
Jesus is the Son of God and that

00:23:46.827 --> 00:23:48.180
he is the Messiah.
 

00:23:48.180 --> 00:23:54.357
Exactly how divine Jesus is in
the Gospel of Matthew is up for

00:23:54.357 --> 00:23:56.038
grabs,
it's not clear,

00:23:56.038 --> 00:23:58.960
but he still--he definitely
seems to believe that Jesus is

